1. Introduction {#s0005}
===============

Radiation therapy plays a critical role in the treatment of cervical cancer, and chemoradiation is the treatment of choice in patients with advanced cervical cancer. However, the dose of radiation that can be delivered to the pelvis is limited by the variations in normal tissue tolerance of other intra-pelvic structures (small and large bowels, rectums, and bladders) to radiation. Target radiation treatment doses exceed the maximal value of small bowel radiation tolerance, leading to acute toxicity (diarrhea, abdominal cramps, and nausea ([@bb0025])).

